1
00:00:50,690 --> 00:00:52,960
Sometimes, I think I'm cursed.

2
00:00:53,087 --> 00:00:56,055
'Cause of something that happened
before I was even born.

3
00:00:56,627 --> 00:01:00,301
See, a long time ago,
there was this family.

4
00:01:01,003 --> 00:01:03,384
The Papá, he was a musician.

5
00:01:03,749 --> 00:01:06,914
He and his family
would sing and dance

6
00:01:06,939 --> 00:01:08,328
and count their blessings.

7
00:01:08,995 --> 00:01:10,646
But he also had a dream.

8
00:01:10,931 --> 00:01:12,939
To play for the world.

9
00:01:15,431 --> 00:01:17,066
And one day...

10
00:01:17,716 --> 00:01:19,716
he left with his guitar...

11
00:01:20,534 --> 00:01:22,550
and never returned.

12
00:01:26,793 --> 00:01:28,373
And my Mamá...

13
00:01:28,627 --> 00:01:31,666
She didn't have time to cry
over that walk-away musician.

14
00:01:33,595 --> 00:01:36,841
After banishing all music
from her life...

15
00:01:37,849 --> 00:01:40,143
she found a way
to provide for her daughter.

16
00:01:44,309 --> 00:01:45,968
She rolled up her sleeves...

17
00:01:46,134 --> 00:01:48,007
and she learned to make shoes.

18
00:01:53,083 --> 00:01:54,591
She could have made candy.

19
00:01:54,616 --> 00:01:56,448
O-o-or fireworks.

20
00:01:57,114 --> 00:01:59,329
Or sparkly underwear for wrestlers.

21
00:02:00,361 --> 00:02:01,940
But no.

22
00:02:02,091 --> 00:02:03,496
She chose shoes.

23
00:02:06,327 --> 00:02:08,192
Then she taught
her daughter to make shoes.

24
00:02:09,740 --> 00:02:12,089
And later, she taught
her son-in-law.

25
00:02:13,565 --> 00:02:15,454
Then her grandkids got roped in.

26
00:02:17,057 --> 00:02:19,732
As her family grew,
so did the business.

27
00:02:21,605 --> 00:02:23,899
Music have torn
her family apart.

28
00:02:25,161 --> 00:02:27,129
But shoes held
them all together.

29
00:02:29,065 --> 00:02:30,708
You see that woman...

30
00:02:30,733 --> 00:02:32,272
was my great-great-grandmother...

31
00:02:32,297 --> 00:02:33,455
Mamá Imelda.

32
00:02:34,559 --> 00:02:36,836
She died way before I was born.

33
00:02:37,384 --> 00:02:39,408
But my family still
tells her story...

34
00:02:39,433 --> 00:02:41,559
every year. And her little girl...

35
00:02:42,068 --> 00:02:44,306
she's my great-grandmother,
Mamá Coco.

36
00:02:44,331 --> 00:02:45,655
Hola, Mamá Coco.

37
00:02:46,377 --> 00:02:48,798
How are you, Julio?

38
00:02:48,917 --> 00:02:50,980
Actually, my name is Miguel.

39
00:02:51,091 --> 00:02:54,703
Mamá Coco has trouble
remembering things.

40
00:02:54,758 --> 00:02:56,845
But it's good to talk to her,
anyway.

41
00:02:56,870 --> 00:02:58,869
So, I tell her
pretty much everything.

42
00:02:58,894 --> 00:03:00,529
I used to run like this.

43
00:03:00,664 --> 00:03:03,172
But now I run like this,
it's just way faster.

44
00:03:03,197 --> 00:03:06,251
The winner is...
luchadora Coco!

45
00:03:06,308 --> 00:03:09,022
I have a dimple on this side,
but not on this side.

46
00:03:09,046 --> 00:03:11,284
Dimple, no dimple.
Dimple, no dimple.

47
00:03:11,309 --> 00:03:13,110
Miguel, eat your food.

48
00:03:13,135 --> 00:03:15,515
My abuelita, she's
Mamá Coco's daughter.

49
00:03:15,539 --> 00:03:18,610
Aw, you're a twig, mijo.
Have some more.

50
00:03:18,635 --> 00:03:19,729
No, gracias.

51
00:03:19,754 --> 00:03:22,302
I asked if you would like
more tamales.

52
00:03:22,905 --> 00:03:23,960
S-Si?

53
00:03:23,985 --> 00:03:26,143
That's what I thought you said!

54
00:03:26,882 --> 00:03:30,366
Abuelita runs the house
just as Mamá Imelda did.

55
00:03:32,144 --> 00:03:33,454
No music!

56
00:03:34,874 --> 00:03:36,358
No music!

57
00:03:36,383 --> 00:03:37,453
♪ aunque la vida ♪

58
00:03:37,478 --> 00:03:39,351
No music!

59
00:03:39,383 --> 00:03:42,971
I think we're the only family
in Mexico who hates music.

60
00:03:42,996 --> 00:03:45,027
And my family's fine with that.

61
00:03:45,052 --> 00:03:45,972
But me...

62
00:03:45,997 --> 00:03:47,274
Be back by lunch, mijo.

63
00:03:47,299 --> 00:03:48,473
Love you, Mamá!

64
00:03:49,576 --> 00:03:51,957
I'm <i>not</i> like the rest
of my family.

65
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:55,028
- Hola, Miguel.
- Hola.

66
00:04:00,537 --> 00:04:02,934
- Muchas gracias!
- De nada, Miguel!

67
00:04:05,941 --> 00:04:07,775
He-hey, Dante!

68
00:04:09,410 --> 00:04:10,291
Sit.

69
00:04:10,338 --> 00:04:11,299
Down.

70
00:04:11,324 --> 00:04:12,418
Roll over.

71
00:04:12,443 --> 00:04:13,419
Shake.

72
00:04:13,744 --> 00:04:14,974
Fist bump.

73
00:04:15,625 --> 00:04:17,332
Good boy, Dante!

74
00:04:20,504 --> 00:04:23,076
I know, I'm not supposed
to love music.

75
00:04:23,370 --> 00:04:25,060
But it's not my fault.

76
00:04:25,211 --> 00:04:26,742
It's his.

77
00:04:26,925 --> 00:04:28,822
Ernesto de la Cruz.

78
00:04:28,846 --> 00:04:31,718
The greatest musician
of all time.

79
00:04:31,817 --> 00:04:35,668
Here in this very plaza,
the young Ernesto de la Cruz

80
00:04:35,693 --> 00:04:38,082
took his first steps
toward becoming

81
00:04:38,107 --> 00:04:41,328
the most beloved singer
in Mexican history.

82
00:04:41,376 --> 00:04:45,716
He started out a total nobody
from Santa Cecilia, like me.

83
00:04:46,773 --> 00:04:48,241
But when he played music,

84
00:04:48,265 --> 00:04:50,899
he made people
fall in love with him.

85
00:04:53,574 --> 00:04:55,424
He starred in movies.

86
00:04:55,551 --> 00:04:57,900
He had the coolest guitar.

87
00:04:58,487 --> 00:04:59,670
He could fly!

88
00:04:59,963 --> 00:05:02,535
And he wrote the best songs.

89
00:05:02,717 --> 00:05:04,662
But my all-time favorite is...

90
00:05:05,019 --> 00:05:07,582
♪ Remember me ♪

91
00:05:07,891 --> 00:05:08,938
♪ Remember me ♪

92
00:05:08,963 --> 00:05:10,622
♪ Though I have to say goodbye ♪

93
00:05:10,685 --> 00:05:12,043
♪ Remember me ♪

94
00:05:12,463 --> 00:05:15,430
♪ Me ♪

95
00:05:15,455 --> 00:05:17,011
Until 1942.

96
00:05:19,072 --> 00:05:22,255
When he was crushed
by a giant bell.

97
00:05:23,255 --> 00:05:25,279
I wanna be just like him.

98
00:05:31,480 --> 00:05:33,503
Sometimes, I look at de la Cruz...

99
00:05:33,528 --> 00:05:35,686
and I get this feeling.

100
00:05:35,710 --> 00:05:37,710
Like we're connected somehow.

101
00:05:37,733 --> 00:05:39,757
Like if he could play music...

102
00:05:39,971 --> 00:05:42,574
maybe someday, I could too!

103
00:05:45,209 --> 00:05:47,194
If it wasn't for my family.

104
00:05:47,219 --> 00:05:49,060
Ay, ay, ay, muchacho!

105
00:05:49,085 --> 00:05:50,044
Huh?

106
00:05:50,069 --> 00:05:52,052
I asked for a shoe shine,
not your life story.

107
00:05:52,077 --> 00:05:53,592
Oh, yeah, sorry.

108
00:05:53,617 --> 00:05:56,956
I just can't really talk about
any of this at home, so.

109
00:05:57,909 --> 00:05:59,361
Look, if I were you,

110
00:05:59,386 --> 00:06:01,361
I'd march right up
to my family and say,

111
00:06:01,386 --> 00:06:03,846
"Hey, I'm a musician.
Deal with it!"

112
00:06:03,871 --> 00:06:05,513
I could never say that.

113
00:06:05,934 --> 00:06:07,863
You are a musician, no?

114
00:06:07,888 --> 00:06:09,275
I-I-I don't know.

115
00:06:09,300 --> 00:06:11,761
I mean, I only really
play for myself.

116
00:06:11,786 --> 00:06:14,952
Ah! Did de la Cruz become
the world's best musician

117
00:06:14,977 --> 00:06:17,159
by hiding his sweet,
sweet skills?

118
00:06:17,191 --> 00:06:18,207
No!

119
00:06:18,232 --> 00:06:20,294
He walked out onto that plaza

120
00:06:20,319 --> 00:06:22,437
and he played out loud!

121
00:06:22,462 --> 00:06:24,605
Ah, Mira, Mira, they're
setting up for tonight.

122
00:06:24,630 --> 00:06:27,494
The music competition for
Día de Muertos.

123
00:06:27,519 --> 00:06:30,352
You wanna be like your hero?
You should sign up!

124
00:06:30,376 --> 00:06:33,177
Unh-unh. My family would freak!

125
00:06:33,519 --> 00:06:37,939
Look, if you're too scared,
then, well, have fun making shoes.

126
00:06:38,241 --> 00:06:41,011
Come on, what did
de la Cruz always say?

127
00:06:41,107 --> 00:06:43,257
Seize your moment?

128
00:06:44,646 --> 00:06:47,130
Show me what you got,
muchacho.

129
00:06:47,956 --> 00:06:50,019
I'll be your first audience.

130
00:06:57,337 --> 00:06:58,504
Miguel!

131
00:06:58,529 --> 00:06:59,361
Ah!

132
00:07:00,544 --> 00:07:01,305
Abuelita!

133
00:07:01,330 --> 00:07:02,909
What are you doing here?

134
00:07:02,934 --> 00:07:04,719
Um... oh... uh...

135
00:07:04,744 --> 00:07:06,481
You leave my grandson alone!

136
00:07:06,537 --> 00:07:09,236
Doña, please! I was just
getting a shine.

137
00:07:09,261 --> 00:07:10,823
I know your tricks, mariachi.

138
00:07:10,848 --> 00:07:11,999
What did he say to you?

139
00:07:12,024 --> 00:07:13,665
He was just showing me
his guitar.

140
00:07:13,976 --> 00:07:15,278
Shame on you!

141
00:07:15,302 --> 00:07:17,968
My grandson is a
is a sweet little

142
00:07:17,992 --> 00:07:21,397
angelito, perrito, cielito!

143
00:07:21,422 --> 00:07:24,048
He wants no part
of your music, mariachi.

144
00:07:24,073 --> 00:07:25,700
You keep away from him.

145
00:07:26,493 --> 00:07:27,708
Y-ay!

146
00:07:29,327 --> 00:07:31,263
Ay, pobrecito!

147
00:07:31,358 --> 00:07:33,509
Estas bien, mijo.

148
00:07:35,001 --> 00:07:37,406
You know better than
to be here in this place.

149
00:07:38,366 --> 00:07:40,993
You will come home.
Now.

150
00:07:51,104 --> 00:07:52,897
How many times
have we told you?

151
00:07:52,922 --> 00:07:55,151
That plaza is crawling
with mariachis.

152
00:07:55,176 --> 00:07:56,946
Yes, Tío Berto.

153
00:07:57,200 --> 00:07:58,375
No, no, no, no, no.

154
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:00,557
Hey, go away, you. Go!

155
00:08:00,582 --> 00:08:02,035
It's just Dante.

156
00:08:02,122 --> 00:08:03,892
Never name a street dog.

157
00:08:03,917 --> 00:08:05,304
They'll follow you forever.

158
00:08:05,488 --> 00:08:07,171
Now, go get my shoe.

159
00:08:13,501 --> 00:08:15,954
I found your son in
Mariachi Plaza.

160
00:08:15,979 --> 00:08:17,382
Ay, Miguel?

161
00:08:17,407 --> 00:08:19,645
You know how abuelita
feels about the plaza.

162
00:08:19,670 --> 00:08:20,938
I was just shining shoes.

163
00:08:20,963 --> 00:08:22,495
A musician's shoes.

164
00:08:24,510 --> 00:08:26,748
But the plaza's where
the foot traffic is.

165
00:08:26,773 --> 00:08:30,533
If abuelita says, "No more plaza",
then no more plaza.

166
00:08:30,558 --> 00:08:31,828
But what about tonight?

167
00:08:31,853 --> 00:08:32,822
What's tonight?

168
00:08:32,847 --> 00:08:35,733
Well, they're having
this talent show.

169
00:08:35,758 --> 00:08:38,768
- A-and I thought I might...
- Sign up?

170
00:08:38,793 --> 00:08:40,900
Well, maybe?

171
00:08:40,925 --> 00:08:43,713
You have to have talent
to be in a talent show.

172
00:08:43,738 --> 00:08:46,643
What are you gonna do?
Shine shoes? Oh!

173
00:08:46,668 --> 00:08:49,849
It's Día de los Muertos.
No one's going any where.

174
00:08:49,874 --> 00:08:51,692
Tonight is about family.

175
00:08:52,367 --> 00:08:54,406
Ofrenda room. Vámonos.

176
00:09:04,842 --> 00:09:07,009
Don't give me that look.

177
00:09:07,034 --> 00:09:09,605
Día de los Muertos is the
one night of the year

178
00:09:09,629 --> 00:09:11,898
our ancestors can come visit us.

179
00:09:11,923 --> 00:09:13,867
We put their photos
on the ofrenda

180
00:09:13,892 --> 00:09:15,955
so their spririts can cross over.

181
00:09:15,980 --> 00:09:17,924
That is very important.

182
00:09:17,949 --> 00:09:20,662
If we don't put them up,
they can't come.

183
00:09:20,687 --> 00:09:22,147
We made all this food.

184
00:09:22,172 --> 00:09:25,267
Set out the things
they loved in life, mijo.

185
00:09:25,292 --> 00:09:28,656
All this work to
bring the family together.

186
00:09:28,681 --> 00:09:31,260
I don't want you sneaking off
to who-knows-where.

187
00:09:31,792 --> 00:09:33,403
Huh! Where are you going?

188
00:09:33,427 --> 00:09:35,974
- I thought we were done.
- Ay, Dios mío.

189
00:09:35,999 --> 00:09:39,554
Being part of this family means
being here for this family.

190
00:09:39,579 --> 00:09:42,174
I don't want to see you
end up like...

191
00:09:42,199 --> 00:09:43,627
Like Mamá Coco's papá?

192
00:09:43,652 --> 00:09:45,318
Never mention that man!

193
00:09:45,343 --> 00:09:46,485
He's better off forgotten.

194
00:09:46,510 --> 00:09:47,826
- But you're the one who...
- Eh, thchhsss!

195
00:09:47,851 --> 00:09:49,264
- I was just...
- Tchsshh!

196
00:09:49,289 --> 00:09:49,986
- But...
- Tchshh.

197
00:09:50,011 --> 00:09:50,756
- I...
- Shhh.

198
00:09:50,781 --> 00:09:51,971
Papá?

199
00:09:51,996 --> 00:09:53,702
Papá is home?

200
00:09:53,726 --> 00:09:56,146
Mamá, cálmese, cálmese.

201
00:09:56,171 --> 00:09:57,950
Papá is coming home?

202
00:09:57,975 --> 00:10:01,697
No, Mamá, it's okay.
I'm here.

203
00:10:02,562 --> 00:10:03,935
Who are you?

204
00:10:04,229 --> 00:10:06,689
Ay... rest, Mamá.

205
00:10:07,570 --> 00:10:10,292
I'm hard on you
because I care, Miguel.

206
00:10:10,888 --> 00:10:11,880
Miguel?

207
00:10:12,332 --> 00:10:13,538
Miguel?

208
00:10:14,300 --> 00:10:15,316
Ay.

209
00:10:16,078 --> 00:10:18,229
What are we going to do
with that boy?

210
00:10:19,150 --> 00:10:21,102
Ha ha ha, you're right.

211
00:10:21,127 --> 00:10:23,285
That's just what he needs.

212
00:10:45,674 --> 00:10:46,667
Huah!

213
00:10:47,087 --> 00:10:49,071
Oh, it's you. Get in here.

214
00:10:49,096 --> 00:10:50,761
Come on, Dante. Hurry up.

215
00:10:52,102 --> 00:10:54,262
You're gonna get me
in trouble, boy.

216
00:10:54,287 --> 00:10:55,840
Someone can hear me.

217
00:11:00,303 --> 00:11:01,969
I wish someone
wanted to hear me.

218
00:11:03,279 --> 00:11:04,850
Other than you.

219
00:11:05,136 --> 00:11:06,755
Ew, okay!

220
00:11:08,723 --> 00:11:09,930
Perfecto.

221
00:11:43,175 --> 00:11:44,667
<i>I have to sing.</i>

222
00:11:44,692 --> 00:11:46,271
<i>I have to play.</i>

223
00:11:46,296 --> 00:11:49,080
<i>The music, it's...
it's not just in me.</i>

224
00:11:49,288 --> 00:11:51,066
<i>It </i>is<i> me.</i>

225
00:11:52,383 --> 00:11:54,050
<i>When life gets me down.</i>

226
00:11:54,075 --> 00:11:55,637
<i>I play my guitar.</i>

227
00:11:56,497 --> 00:11:59,814
<i>The rest of the world may
follow the rules, but I...</i>

228
00:11:59,839 --> 00:12:01,822
<i>must follow my heart.</i>

229
00:12:02,347 --> 00:12:03,234
Ugh.

230
00:12:03,259 --> 00:12:04,776
<i>You know that feeling...</i>

231
00:12:04,801 --> 00:12:06,386
<i>like there's a song in the air</i>

232
00:12:06,411 --> 00:12:08,601
<i>and it's playing just for you?</i>

233
00:12:12,440 --> 00:12:14,972
<i>♪ A feeling so close ♪</i>

234
00:12:14,997 --> 00:12:19,045
<i>♪ You could reach out
and touch it ♪</i>

235
00:12:19,070 --> 00:12:21,886
<i>♪ I never knew ♪</i>

236
00:12:21,911 --> 00:12:24,626
<i>♪ I could want something
so much ♪</i>

237
00:12:24,651 --> 00:12:26,292
<i>♪ But it's true ♪</i>

238
00:12:26,992 --> 00:12:28,556
<i>You must have faith, sister.</i>

239
00:12:28,581 --> 00:12:30,897
<i>Oh, but Padre,
he will never listen.</i>

240
00:12:30,922 --> 00:12:33,097
<i>He will listen to music!</i>

241
00:12:33,137 --> 00:12:35,930
<i>♪ Only a song, only a song ♪</i>

242
00:12:35,954 --> 00:12:39,724
<i>♪ Has the power
to change a heart ♪</i>

243
00:12:43,416 --> 00:12:46,425
<i>Never underestimate
the power of music.</i>

244
00:12:50,924 --> 00:12:52,337
<i>But my father,</i>

245
00:12:52,361 --> 00:12:54,130
<i>he will never give
his permission.</i>

246
00:12:54,155 --> 00:12:56,321
<i>I am done
asking permission.</i>

247
00:12:56,346 --> 00:12:57,425
<i>When you see your moment,</i>

248
00:12:57,450 --> 00:12:59,044
<i>you mustn't let it pass you by.</i>

249
00:12:59,069 --> 00:13:01,124
<i>You must seize it.</i>

250
00:13:01,250 --> 00:13:02,512
<i>Señor de la Cruz,</i>

251
00:13:02,584 --> 00:13:05,076
<i>what did it take for you
to seize your moment?</i>

252
00:13:06,901 --> 00:13:09,560
<i>I had to have faith
in my dream.</i>

253
00:13:09,585 --> 00:13:11,600
<i>No one was going to hand it to me.</i>

254
00:13:11,624 --> 00:13:14,043
<i>It was up to me to
reach for that dream.</i>

255
00:13:14,067 --> 00:13:15,662
<i>Grab it tight...</i>

256
00:13:15,687 --> 00:13:17,646
<i>and make it come true.</i>

257
00:13:22,172 --> 00:13:23,942
No more hiding, Dante.

258
00:13:23,967 --> 00:13:25,617
I gotta seize my moment.

259
00:13:26,627 --> 00:13:29,738
I'm gonna play in Mariachi Plaza
if it kills me.

260
00:13:33,536 --> 00:13:36,394
Día de Muertos has begun!

261
00:13:36,822 --> 00:13:38,346
No, no, no, no, no.

262
00:13:38,371 --> 00:13:40,274
We have to make a clear path.

263
00:13:40,299 --> 00:13:42,588
The petals guide
our ancestors home.

264
00:13:50,526 --> 00:13:51,661
- Mamá!
- Hunh!

265
00:13:51,686 --> 00:13:53,177
Where should we put this table?

266
00:13:53,202 --> 00:13:54,409
In the courtyard, mijos.

267
00:13:54,434 --> 00:13:55,695
You want it down
by the kitchen?

268
00:13:55,720 --> 00:13:58,394
Si, eh, next to the other one.

269
00:14:00,553 --> 00:14:01,950
Get under, get under!

270
00:14:03,053 --> 00:14:03,799
Miguel?

271
00:14:03,824 --> 00:14:04,776
Uh, nothing.

272
00:14:05,951 --> 00:14:07,086
Mamá, Papá, I...

273
00:14:07,111 --> 00:14:09,222
Miguel, your abuelita have

274
00:14:09,247 --> 00:14:12,118
the most wonderful idea.

275
00:14:12,143 --> 00:14:13,531
We've all decided...

276
00:14:13,556 --> 00:14:16,286
it's time you joined us
in the workshop!

277
00:14:16,373 --> 00:14:17,097
What?

278
00:14:17,122 --> 00:14:18,802
No more shining shoes.

279
00:14:18,827 --> 00:14:21,654
You will be making them,
every day, after school.

280
00:14:21,678 --> 00:14:24,614
Oh, our Miguelitititito

281
00:14:24,639 --> 00:14:27,344
carrying on the family tradition.

282
00:14:27,368 --> 00:14:29,368
And on Día de los Muertos!

283
00:14:29,393 --> 00:14:32,464
Your ancestors
would be so proud.

284
00:14:32,528 --> 00:14:35,989
You'll craft huaraches
just like your Tía Victoria.

285
00:14:36,014 --> 00:14:38,647
And wing tips just like
your Papá Julio.

286
00:14:38,672 --> 00:14:41,466
But what if I'm no good
at making shoes?

287
00:14:41,491 --> 00:14:42,871
Ay, Miguel.

288
00:14:42,896 --> 00:14:45,317
You have your family here
to guide you.

289
00:14:45,342 --> 00:14:47,658
You are a Rivera.

290
00:14:47,683 --> 00:14:50,612
And a Rivera is?

291
00:14:50,636 --> 00:14:52,636
A shoemaker...

292
00:14:52,660 --> 00:14:53,691
through and through.

293
00:14:53,716 --> 00:14:55,064
That's my boy!

294
00:14:55,089 --> 00:14:57,945
Haha! Berto!
Break out the good stuff!

295
00:14:59,629 --> 00:15:01,748
Mm, mm, mm, mwah!

296
00:15:09,598 --> 00:15:11,154
Dante!

297
00:15:11,900 --> 00:15:13,273
No, Dante, stop!

298
00:15:18,879 --> 00:15:19,911
Hunh!

299
00:15:22,220 --> 00:15:23,204
Ah!

300
00:15:23,748 --> 00:15:24,883
No, no, no, no, no!

301
00:15:25,971 --> 00:15:26,796
No.

302
00:15:38,651 --> 00:15:41,246
De la Cruz' guitar?

303
00:15:41,389 --> 00:15:42,492
Ah?

304
00:15:43,214 --> 00:15:44,555
Papá?

305
00:15:45,329 --> 00:15:46,798
Mamá Coco.

306
00:15:46,877 --> 00:15:49,695
Is your papá Ernesto de la Cruz?

307
00:15:49,720 --> 00:15:52,345
Papá! Papá!

308
00:16:02,530 --> 00:16:03,522
Haha!

309
00:16:03,696 --> 00:16:04,783
Papá, Papá!

310
00:16:04,808 --> 00:16:06,037
It's him!

311
00:16:06,062 --> 00:16:07,808
I know who my
great-great-grandfather was!

312
00:16:07,833 --> 00:16:09,753
Miguel, get down from there.

313
00:16:09,778 --> 00:16:12,324
Mamá Coco's father
was Ernesto de la Cruz!

314
00:16:12,349 --> 00:16:13,960
What are you talking about?

315
00:16:13,985 --> 00:16:15,817
I'm gonna be a musician!

316
00:16:17,692 --> 00:16:19,049
What is all this?

317
00:16:19,074 --> 00:16:21,327
You keep secrets
from your own family?

318
00:16:21,352 --> 00:16:23,272
It's all that time he spends
in the plaza.

319
00:16:23,297 --> 00:16:25,233
Fills his head
with crazy fantasies.

320
00:16:25,258 --> 00:16:26,464
It's not a fantasy.

321
00:16:26,489 --> 00:16:28,718
That man was
Ernesto de la Cruz.

322
00:16:28,743 --> 00:16:30,441
The greatest musician
of all time.

323
00:16:30,466 --> 00:16:32,267
We've never known
anything about this man.

324
00:16:32,292 --> 00:16:35,847
Or whoever he was,
he still abandoned his family.

325
00:16:35,872 --> 00:16:37,268
It's no future for my son.

326
00:16:37,293 --> 00:16:40,283
Well, Papá, y-you said
my family would guide me.

327
00:16:40,308 --> 00:16:42,547
Well, de la Cruz <i>is</i> my family.

328
00:16:42,572 --> 00:16:44,284
I'm supposed to play music.

329
00:16:44,309 --> 00:16:46,745
Never! That man's music
was a curse.

330
00:16:46,769 --> 00:16:48,332
I will not allow it.

331
00:16:48,357 --> 00:16:50,205
- If you would just...
- Miguel.

332
00:16:50,230 --> 00:16:51,460
You will listen to your family.

333
00:16:51,485 --> 00:16:53,230
No more music.

334
00:16:53,255 --> 00:16:54,499
Just listen to me play.

335
00:16:54,524 --> 00:16:55,905
End of argument.

336
00:16:57,646 --> 00:16:59,511
You want to end up
like that man?

337
00:16:59,536 --> 00:17:00,695
Forgotten?

338
00:17:00,720 --> 00:17:02,964
Left off your family's ofrenda?

339
00:17:02,989 --> 00:17:05,157
I don't care if I'm on some
stupid ofrenda.

340
00:17:05,182 --> 00:17:07,149
- Hunh!
- Hunh!

341
00:17:08,878 --> 00:17:10,227
- No!
- Mamá!

342
00:17:14,788 --> 00:17:15,804
There.

343
00:17:15,829 --> 00:17:17,145
No guitar.

344
00:17:17,367 --> 00:17:18,636
No music.

345
00:17:21,010 --> 00:17:22,796
Aw, come.

346
00:17:22,820 --> 00:17:26,073
You'll feel better after
you eat with your family.

347
00:17:26,098 --> 00:17:27,772
I don't wanna be in this family!

348
00:17:28,431 --> 00:17:30,130
Miguel, Miguel!

349
00:17:49,133 --> 00:17:50,537
I-I wanna play in the plaza.

350
00:17:50,562 --> 00:17:51,609
Like de la Cruz.

351
00:17:51,640 --> 00:17:53,079
C-can I still sign up?

352
00:17:53,103 --> 00:17:54,148
You got an instrument?

353
00:17:54,244 --> 00:17:56,839
No. But if I can borrow a guitar.

354
00:17:56,864 --> 00:17:58,807
Musicians gotta bring
their own instruments.

355
00:17:58,832 --> 00:18:01,658
You find a guitar, kid,
I'll put you on the list.

356
00:18:04,267 --> 00:18:06,608
Hey, excuse me,
can I borrow your guitar?

357
00:18:06,633 --> 00:18:07,957
Sorry, muchaco.

358
00:18:07,982 --> 00:18:09,513
You guys have a spare guitar?

359
00:18:09,538 --> 00:18:10,465
No.

360
00:18:10,490 --> 00:18:12,818
I need a guitar
just for a little bit.

361
00:18:12,842 --> 00:18:14,395
Get outta here, kid.

362
00:18:27,335 --> 00:18:29,089
Great-great-grandfather.

363
00:18:29,842 --> 00:18:31,422
What am I supposed to do?

364
00:19:09,784 --> 00:19:11,411
No, no, no, no.
Dante, stop.

365
00:19:11,436 --> 00:19:13,498
Cállate, shh.

366
00:19:35,089 --> 00:19:36,423
I'm sorry.

367
00:20:12,592 --> 00:20:14,314
Señor de la Cruz.

368
00:20:15,306 --> 00:20:16,742
Please don't be mad.

369
00:20:16,767 --> 00:20:18,258
I-I'm Miguel.

370
00:20:18,283 --> 00:20:20,085
Your great-great-grandson.

371
00:20:20,783 --> 00:20:22,664
I-I need to borrow this.

372
00:20:25,490 --> 00:20:28,045
Our family thinks
music is a curse.

373
00:20:28,341 --> 00:20:31,698
None of them understand.
But I know you would have.

374
00:20:31,889 --> 00:20:34,389
You would have told me
to follow my heart.

375
00:20:34,413 --> 00:20:36,413
To seize my moment.

376
00:20:37,603 --> 00:20:40,198
So, if it's all right with you...

377
00:20:40,222 --> 00:20:41,881
I'm gonna play in the Plaza.

378
00:20:41,906 --> 00:20:43,762
Just like you did!

379
00:20:51,796 --> 00:20:52,955
Huh?

380
00:20:52,980 --> 00:20:54,416
What's going on?

381
00:20:54,441 --> 00:20:56,178
Somebody stole
de la Cruz' guitar.

382
00:20:56,257 --> 00:20:58,780
The window is broken, look!

383
00:21:03,113 --> 00:21:04,613
All right, who's in there?

384
00:21:04,638 --> 00:21:06,669
I'm sorry, i-it's not
what it looks like.

385
00:21:06,694 --> 00:21:08,519
De la Cruz is my...

386
00:21:09,257 --> 00:21:09,931
Huh!

387
00:21:09,956 --> 00:21:11,209
There's nobody here!

388
00:21:27,082 --> 00:21:28,312
- Miguel!
- Mamá!

389
00:21:28,463 --> 00:21:30,066
Miguel, come home!

390
00:21:36,161 --> 00:21:39,288
Dios mio, little boy!
Are you okay?

391
00:21:39,590 --> 00:21:41,153
Here, let me help you.

392
00:21:42,201 --> 00:21:43,629
Thanks. I...

393
00:21:44,637 --> 00:21:46,343
- Aaah!
- Aaah!

394
00:21:49,463 --> 00:21:50,455
Aah!

395
00:21:52,239 --> 00:21:53,191
Aah!

396
00:21:54,429 --> 00:21:55,484
Do you mind?

397
00:21:55,707 --> 00:21:57,112
- Aah!
- Aah!

398
00:22:17,113 --> 00:22:19,438
Look how big she's getting.

399
00:22:22,851 --> 00:22:24,661
Uh! Dante?

400
00:22:24,686 --> 00:22:26,009
You can see me?

401
00:22:26,874 --> 00:22:29,343
Wait! What's going on?

402
00:22:29,755 --> 00:22:31,901
Dante! Dante!

403
00:22:32,504 --> 00:22:34,004
Oh, I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

404
00:22:34,029 --> 00:22:34,884
Miguel?

405
00:22:35,231 --> 00:22:36,813
- Miguel?
- Miguel?

406
00:22:40,183 --> 00:22:41,581
Y-you're here!

407
00:22:41,606 --> 00:22:42,636
Here here.

408
00:22:42,661 --> 00:22:43,883
And you can see us?

409
00:22:43,908 --> 00:22:46,691
Our Miguelitititito!

410
00:22:46,717 --> 00:22:48,153
Remind me how I know you?

411
00:22:48,178 --> 00:22:49,646
We're your family, mijo.

412
00:22:52,186 --> 00:22:53,678
Tía Rosita?

413
00:22:53,703 --> 00:22:54,964
Si.

414
00:22:56,742 --> 00:22:57,901
Papá Julio?

415
00:22:57,944 --> 00:22:59,134
Hola!

416
00:22:59,353 --> 00:23:01,393
Tía Vic...toria?

417
00:23:01,552 --> 00:23:03,718
He doesn't seem
entirely dead.

418
00:23:04,274 --> 00:23:06,289
He's not quite alive, either.

419
00:23:06,314 --> 00:23:07,790
We need Mamá Imelda.

420
00:23:07,815 --> 00:23:09,338
She'll know how to fix this.

421
00:23:09,363 --> 00:23:10,544
Oye!

422
00:23:11,560 --> 00:23:13,076
It's Mamá Imelda!

423
00:23:13,101 --> 00:23:14,473
She couldn't cross over!

424
00:23:14,498 --> 00:23:15,307
She's stuck!

425
00:23:15,332 --> 00:23:16,808
On the other side!

426
00:23:16,918 --> 00:23:18,299
Tío Oscar?

427
00:23:18,506 --> 00:23:19,752
Tío Felipe?

428
00:23:19,783 --> 00:23:21,037
Oh, hey, Miguel.

429
00:23:21,783 --> 00:23:24,457
I have a feeling this has
something to do with you.

430
00:23:24,497 --> 00:23:26,275
But if Mamá Imelda
can't come to us...

431
00:23:26,300 --> 00:23:28,061
Then we are going to her!

432
00:23:28,086 --> 00:23:29,045
- Whoa!
- Vámonos!

433
00:23:42,874 --> 00:23:44,271
Whoa.

434
00:23:44,296 --> 00:23:46,938
Come on, Miguel, it's-it's okay.

435
00:23:59,666 --> 00:24:00,618
Dante?

436
00:24:00,903 --> 00:24:01,999
Dante!

437
00:24:03,055 --> 00:24:04,182
Dante, wait up!

438
00:24:06,698 --> 00:24:08,237
You've gotta stay with me, boy.

439
00:24:08,460 --> 00:24:10,150
You don't know...

440
00:24:10,936 --> 00:24:12,016
where...

441
00:24:31,690 --> 00:24:33,293
This isn't a dream, then.

442
00:24:33,706 --> 00:24:35,172
You're all really out there.

443
00:24:35,197 --> 00:24:36,317
You thought we weren't?

444
00:24:36,342 --> 00:24:37,547
Oh, I don't know.

445
00:24:37,572 --> 00:24:39,888
I thought it might have been
one of those made-up things...

446
00:24:39,913 --> 00:24:41,541
that adults tell kids, like...

447
00:24:41,566 --> 00:24:42,239
vitamins.

448
00:24:42,264 --> 00:24:44,548
Miguel, vitamins
are a real thing.

449
00:24:44,573 --> 00:24:46,421
Well, now I'm thinking
maybe they could be.

450
00:24:46,446 --> 00:24:47,359
Hunh!

451
00:24:47,384 --> 00:24:48,930
Mija, it's not nice to stare at...

452
00:24:48,978 --> 00:24:50,756
Ay, Santa Ma...

453
00:24:58,804 --> 00:24:59,923
Are those?

454
00:24:59,948 --> 00:25:01,582
Alebrijes!

455
00:25:01,606 --> 00:25:03,606
- But those are...
- Real alebrijes.

456
00:25:03,631 --> 00:25:05,289
Spirit creatures.

457
00:25:05,314 --> 00:25:06,941
They guide souls
on their journey.

458
00:25:06,966 --> 00:25:09,591
Watch your step,
they make cacitas everywhere.

459
00:25:09,615 --> 00:25:11,560
<i>Welcome back
to the Land of the Dead.</i>

460
00:25:11,585 --> 00:25:14,290
<i>Please have all offerings
ready for re-entry.</i>

461
00:25:14,315 --> 00:25:15,609
Welcome back.

462
00:25:15,634 --> 00:25:16,840
Anything to declare?

463
00:25:16,865 --> 00:25:18,442
Some churros, from my family.

464
00:25:18,466 --> 00:25:19,680
How wonderful!

465
00:25:19,704 --> 00:25:22,148
<i>If you're experiencing
travel issues...</i>

466
00:25:22,173 --> 00:25:24,371
<i>Agents at the Department of
Family Reunion</i>

467
00:25:24,396 --> 00:25:26,228
<i>are available to assist you.</i>

468
00:25:26,253 --> 00:25:27,840
Next family, please.

469
00:25:31,609 --> 00:25:34,347
Oh, your photos are
in your son's ofrenda.

470
00:25:34,372 --> 00:25:35,395
Have a great visit.

471
00:25:35,419 --> 00:25:36,577
- Gracias.
- Gracias.

472
00:25:36,602 --> 00:25:38,609
<i>And remember to return
before sunrise.</i>

473
00:25:38,634 --> 00:25:39,832
<i>Enjoy your visit!</i>

474
00:25:39,857 --> 00:25:40,800
Next?

475
00:25:42,037 --> 00:25:44,060
Your photo's on your
dentist's ofrenda.

476
00:25:44,085 --> 00:25:45,497
Enjoy your visit.

477
00:25:45,522 --> 00:25:46,521
Grashiash.

478
00:25:46,546 --> 00:25:47,578
Next?

479
00:25:49,014 --> 00:25:51,887
Yes, it is I, Frida Kahlo.

480
00:25:51,912 --> 00:25:53,363
Shall we skip the scanner?

481
00:25:53,388 --> 00:25:54,856
I'm on so many ofrendas

482
00:25:54,881 --> 00:25:57,522
it will just overwhelm your
blinky thingy.

483
00:25:58,785 --> 00:25:59,817
Whoa, shoot.

484
00:25:59,855 --> 00:26:01,974
Looks like no one
put up your photo...

485
00:26:01,999 --> 00:26:03,420
Frida?

486
00:26:03,444 --> 00:26:05,991
Okay, when I said
I was Frida, just now...

487
00:26:06,015 --> 00:26:06,856
That.

488
00:26:06,888 --> 00:26:07,793
That was a lie.

489
00:26:07,817 --> 00:26:09,817
And I apologize for doing that.

490
00:26:09,841 --> 00:26:11,841
No photo on an ofrenda,
no crossing the bridge.

491
00:26:11,865 --> 00:26:12,754
You know what?

492
00:26:12,779 --> 00:26:15,666
I'm just gonna zip right over.
You won't even know I'm gone.

493
00:26:18,175 --> 00:26:19,310
Haha!

494
00:26:24,671 --> 00:26:26,448
Almost... there...

495
00:26:26,473 --> 00:26:28,615
Just a little... further...

496
00:26:31,085 --> 00:26:31,989
Ugh.

497
00:26:33,140 --> 00:26:34,378
Upsy daisy.

498
00:26:34,403 --> 00:26:36,592
Fine. Okay. Fine, who cares?

499
00:26:36,784 --> 00:26:38,721
Dumb flower bridge!

500
00:26:38,746 --> 00:26:42,212
Aw, I don't know what I'd do
if no one put up my photo.

501
00:26:42,237 --> 00:26:43,046
Next?

502
00:26:43,071 --> 00:26:44,841
Oh, come mijo, it's our turn.

503
00:26:44,866 --> 00:26:46,460
Welcome back, amigo.

504
00:26:46,485 --> 00:26:47,739
Anything to declare?

505
00:26:47,764 --> 00:26:49,572
A-as a matter of fact...

506
00:26:49,628 --> 00:26:50,810
Yes.

507
00:26:51,629 --> 00:26:52,375
Hola.

508
00:27:00,125 --> 00:27:01,789
<i>Paging Marta Gonzalez Ramos...</i>

509
00:27:02,146 --> 00:27:03,250
<i>Marta Gonzalez Ramos...</i>

510
00:27:03,281 --> 00:27:04,670
<i>Please report to level seven.</i>

511
00:27:09,554 --> 00:27:10,490
Whoa.

512
00:27:14,224 --> 00:27:15,764
I miss my nose.

513
00:27:25,247 --> 00:27:26,969
Come on, help us out, amigo.

514
00:27:26,994 --> 00:27:28,755
We gotta get to a
dozen ofrendas tonight.

515
00:27:28,779 --> 00:27:31,573
We are not visiting
your ex-wife, Stanley,

516
00:27:31,598 --> 00:27:32,692
por Día de Muertos.

517
00:27:32,717 --> 00:27:35,247
I demand to speak to the
person in charge.

518
00:27:35,272 --> 00:27:37,019
I'm sorry, señora, it says here

519
00:27:37,044 --> 00:27:38,328
no one put up your photo.

520
00:27:38,353 --> 00:27:42,677
My family always, always
put my photo up in the ofrenda

521
00:27:42,701 --> 00:27:45,732
That devil box tells you
nothing but lies.

522
00:27:46,209 --> 00:27:47,455
Mamá Imelda?

523
00:27:48,550 --> 00:27:50,305
Oh, mi familia.

524
00:27:50,330 --> 00:27:52,233
They wouldn't let me
cross the bridge.

525
00:27:52,258 --> 00:27:54,677
Tell this woman and her
devil box

526
00:27:54,702 --> 00:27:57,138
that my photo is in the ofrenda.

527
00:27:57,163 --> 00:28:00,568
Well, w-we never
made it to the ofrenda.

528
00:28:00,593 --> 00:28:01,631
What?

529
00:28:01,656 --> 00:28:03,235
We ran into a...

530
